Leaning back into things that bring me joy and fulfillment. Needed to take a break from photography to fall back in love with it again. 

These were taken this past summer during on our hike in Squamish. After trekking for nearly 4 hours and climbing over 2,145 of elevation, we eventually made it to the top.

This hike pushed us to our limits, testing not just our physical endurance but also our mental strength. Every step taken was a triumph, every obstacle overcome a victory.

Sometimes it takes facing adversity to discover just how strong we truly are.

In light of last nights season finale of The Good Doctor, I wanted to share some of my favorite moments from my time on set. I loved playing the role of Dr. Daniel Perez and to say it was nothing short of an incredible experience to work with such genuine, talented people would be an understatement. Thank you to the cast, crew, and everyone at ABC for choosing me to be a part of something so special and meaningful. And the biggest thank you to TGD fans for embracing me. I’ve enjoyed every single moment. Until we meet again. Dr. Perez signing off.

Got my ass handed to me this morning by these two. Ever since the pandemic, I've grown accustomed to training alone, but every now and then, I embrace the challenge and competitive spirit that comes with training alongside a partner.

Boy, where has the time gone? To think that we're already more than halfway through the year baffles me. So much has changed in the span of a year—from living in a new city, working on a different project, starting a TV and film production company with my wife, to going from a one-dog household to a two-dog household. I am grateful for all of the changes that have occurred because they've forced me to grow as an individual.

One of the things I told myself last year was that I was going to relinquish control, or whatever control I THOUGHT I had over my life. I became so fixated on my long-term goals that I was inadvertently blocking myself off from all of the spontaneous blessings that God had in store for me.

Don't get me wrong. It's healthy to have goals for yourself. They allow us to have an idea of which direction we should be heading in. Goals provide us with the discipline we need to stay on track. But as with most things in life, it's all about finding balance, a perfect harmony.

Aside from directing my second film towards the tail end of this year and our trip to Italy in September, I couldn't tell you what the rest of the year has in store. The one thing I do know is that I’m open to it all—the good, the bad, and everything in between.

Months and months of preparation have finally brought us to this point. Just a few days ago, we wrapped principal photography on one of the most important stories I’ve ever had the privilege of telling.

To say that getting to this point was easy would be a bald-faced lie. We faced just about every obstacle one can imagine, from funding issues to locations and actors dropping out at the last minute. Even some of our closest friends and family unknowingly planted doubts in our minds. But one of the biggest challenges was the deafening sound of self-doubt that persisted throughout the journey. 'What if we fail? What if nobody watches? Am I the right person to tell this story?' These were only a fraction of the thoughts that passed through my mind during the pre-production stage.

The reality is, if it was solely up to me, I probably would have talked my way out of following through with telling this story. Fortunately, I was surrounded by some of the best producing partners one could ever ask for. Thank you to @jazminlarracuente, @rosamxo, @jake.ambrose, and @kellylamorwilson for your commitment and dedication to telling this story in the most responsible, raw, and honest way possible. This truly was a team effort, and I couldn't be prouder of you all.

Last but not least, thank you to each and every cast and crew member for gracing us with four days of your time and energy. I had the absolute honor and privilege of working with some of the most talented, professional, and down-to-earth people I've ever met. Some were friends we've worked with in the past, and others were new to our circle, but it didn't take long for everyone to feel like family.

To anyone who aspires to be a filmmaker but is constantly met with feelings of self-doubt, or others instilling their own fears onto you, my advice to you is this: protect what's yours and don't be afraid to share your truth with the world. Everyone has a story, and we all deserve for it to be told.
